      }
    },
    {
      "node_id": "chunk:edward_pellew_3rd_viscount_exmouth_0",
      "passage_index": 12,
      "title": "Edward Pellew, 3rd Viscount Exmouth",
      "score": 0.04235073081126554,
      "text": "Edward Pellew, 3rd Viscount Exmouth\nEdward Pellew, 3rd Viscount Exmouth (14 February 1811 – 11 February 1876), was a British peer who inherited the title of Viscount Exmouth from his father and held the title for 42 years. He was the grandson of Edward Pellew, 1st Viscount Exmouth.",
      "score_breakdown": {
        "dense": 0.05024558604486367,
        "graph": 0.04905219495530172,
        "fact": 0.0
      }
    },
    {
      "node_id": "chunk:edward_malet_0",
      "passage_index": 2,
      "title": "Edward Malet",
      "score": 0.04234684179391229,
      "text": "Edward Malet\nEdward Malet came from a family of diplomats; his father was Sir Alexander Malet, British minister to Württemberg and later to the German Confederation. After three years at Eton College, Edward Malet entered the foreign service at the age of 17.",
      "score_breakdown": {
        "dense": 0.050239029653390305,
        "graph": 0.04905125161515874,
        "fact": 0.0
      }
    },
    {
      "node_id": "chunk:edmund_of_woodstock_1st_earl_of_kent_0",
      "passage_index": 1,
      "title": "Edmund of Woodstock, 1st Earl of Kent",
      "score": 0.04233633308422623,
      "text": "Edmund of Woodstock, 1st Earl of Kent\nEdmund of Woodstock, 1st Earl of Kent (5 August 130119 March 1330) was the sixth son of Edward I of England, and a younger half-brother of Edward II. Edward I had intended to make substantial grants of land to Edmund, but when the king died in 1307, Edward II failed to follow through on his father's intentions, much due to his favouritism towards Piers Gaveston. Edmund still remained loyal to his brother, and in 1321 he was created Earl of Kent. He played an important part in Edward's administration, acting both as diplomat and military commander, and in 1321–22 helped suppress a rebellion against the King.",
      "score_breakdown": {
        "dense": 0.05001370689707472,
        "graph": 0.04942931430278376,
        "fact": 0.0
      }
    },
    {
      "node_id": "chunk:edward_dannreuther_0",
      "passage_index": 19,
      "title": "Edward Dannreuther",
      "score": 0.04232756330062326,
      "text": "Edward Dannreuther\nEdward George Dannreuther (4 November 1844, Strasbourg – 12 February 1905, Hastings) was a German pianist and writer on music, resident from 1863 in England. His father had crossed the Atlantic, moving to Cincinnati, and there established a piano manufacturing business. Young Edward, under pressure from his father to enter banking as a career, a prospect he found uncongenial, escaped to Leipzig in 1859.",
      "score_breakdown": {
        "dense": 0.050004277544240694,
        "graph": 0.04941736883763625,
        "fact": 0.0
      }
